   <category name='objects'>

      <section name='adverts'>

         <para number='1' comment='Examine advert - loc 518'>
         The advert shows a selection of commercial messages from various organizations and companies on Venus.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='advert - 1'>
         A jolly chap raises a mug to the camera, and exhorts you to visit the Urban Spaceman bar, close to the spaceport, and drink in the company of authentic spacemen.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='advert - 2'>
         An announcement from the Venus power plant trumpets the fact that they will be bringing a new generator online soon, which will double their capacity.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='advert - 3'>
         A spokesman from the Venus Freedom Party rants on about the evil and corrupt Galactic Administration, which is strangling the freedom of Venusians... and on, and on. He closes by asking for donations to aid the cause.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='advert - 4'>
         The Venus Museum announces its new exhibit, entitled Myths and Legends. An earnest voice tells you it is both entertaining and educational, while the screen displays pictures of the some of the exhibits.
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='advert - 5'>
         Cheesy saxophone music plays, and a silhouette of people dancing slowly and seductively appears on the screen. Lettering appears: "Dr Fogg's Marital Arts Emporium. You know what we offer." The picture fades to black, and the music is replaced by a man laughing the dirtiest laugh you have ever heard.
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='adverts - 6'>
         An attractive woman in a slinky black dress holds out her arm, showing you a gold bracelet studded with Venusian opals. In a sultry voice, she says, "I had this delivered... by Armstrong Cuthbert."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='adverts - 7'>
         A smart executive in the latest cut-away pinstripe shorts brandishes a locked metal briefcase. "I had this delivered... by Armstrong Cuthbert," he says.
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='adverts - 8'>
         A small furry alien holds a poster showing an old Earth baseball star. He speaks in his native language, which sounds like somebody gargling; the subtitle translates his speech as, "I had this delivered... by Armstrong Cuthbert."
         </para>

         <para number='10' comment='adverts - 9'>
         A gorgeous hunk of a man, dressed in not very much, holds a single white rose. He lifts it to his nose and inhales the scent deeply, his chest muscles rippling as he takes in the breath, then he looks out of the viewscreen and says, "I had this delivered... by Armstrong Cuthbert."
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='adverts - 10'>
         A droid appears on the screen, with its head all battered and dented, hanging off its shoulders by a few wires. It removes the head and drops it, then picks up a new head and slots it in place. It shakes the new head backwards and forwards a few times, then says in a mechanical voice, "I had this delivered... by Armstrong Cuthbert."
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='burbage'>

         <para number='1' comment='Burbage - variable unknown'>
         Burbage notices you and comes to the front of the stage. "Hamlet," says the droid. "I was born to play this role. There's no reason he has to be played by a human - robots can act just as well, and can show real emotion. Or at least we can fake it so you can't tell the difference." It jumps off the stage into the aisle. "You would like to hear me recite, I am sure."
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Burbage - variable is 1'>
         "Oh good," says the droid, regardless of what you actually said. He takes a heroic stance, fixes his sensors on you with a piercing gaze, and begins: "To be, or not to be--that is the question: Whether 'tis nobler in the mind to suffer The slings and arrows of outrageous fortune Or to take arms against a sea of troubles And by opposing end them."
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='Burbage - variable is 2'>
         Ignoring your interruption, the droid actor continues: "To die, to sleep-- No more--and by a sleep to say we end The heartache, and the thousand natural shocks That flesh is heir to. 'Tis a consummation   Devoutly to be wished."
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Burbage - variable is 3'>
         And still it goes on: "To die, to sleep-- To sleep--perchance to dream: ay, there's the rub, For in that sleep of death what dreams may come When we have shuffled off this mortal coil, Must give us pause. There's the respect That makes calamity of so long life."
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Burbage - variable is 4'>
         It's really getting into the role now, oblivious to your comment, flecks of lub-oil flying out of its orifice as it continues with intensity: "For who would bear the whips and scorns of time, Th' oppressor's wrong, the proud man's contumely The pangs of despised love, the law's delay, The insolence of office, and the spurns That patient merit of th' unworthy takes, When he himself might his quietus make With a bare bodkin?"
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Burbage - variable is 5'>
         You may as well resign yourself to hearing the whole soliloquy because nothing is going to stop the droid now: "Who would fardels bear, To grunt and sweat under a weary life, But that the dread of something after death, The undiscovered country, from whose bourn No traveller returns, puzzles the will, And makes us rather bear those ills we have Than fly to others that we know not of?"
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='Burbage - variable is 6'>
         Never have you seen a droid so impassioned, as it launches itself into the final stanza of Hamlet's famous speech: "Thus conscience does make cowards of us all, And thus the native hue of resolution Is sicklied o'er with the pale cast of thought, And enterprise of great pitch and moment With this regard their currents turn awry And lose the name of action. -- Soft you now, The fair Ophelia! -- Nymph, in thy orisons Be all my sins remembered."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='Burbage - variable is 7'>
         "Well, I am sure you were impressed," says the thespian droid. "I've won awards for my Hamlet, you know. I wowed them on Mars, they lauded me on the Moon and cheered me to the rafters on Mercury. Even the little provincial planets, Titan and Castillo, heaped praises upon me. But will they let me play on Earth? No, they will not, because they are afraid that I will over-shadow their human actors," it says this with a sneer.
         </para>

         <para number='9'>
         "But talent will out, and one day they will treat me as I deserve." Its eyes gaze into the distance, as it ponders the applause that it clearly feels is its due.
         </para>

         <para number='10'>
         "Now, it was absolutely fascinating to hear all about you, but I must get on with rehearsals." The droid jumps back up onto the stage.
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='Burbage has finished his speech'>
         Burbage ignores you and carries on rehearsing its lines in a monotonous mutter.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='castle'>

         <para number='1' comment='Bouncy castle - 1 - player'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, you start jumping up and down. You bounce, bounce, bounce, then fall over in a very ungainly fashion, looking like a complete twit. You get off and hope nobody noticed your pratfall.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Bouncy castle - 1 - roomex'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, %s starts jumping up and down, with a bounce, bounce bounce... and then falls over in a very ungainly fashion, looking like a complete twit. What a pratfall!
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='Bouncy castle - 2 - player'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, you start jumping up and down. You bounce a few times, then decide to liven things up by bouncing sideways into the walls. After you almost knock over one of the children, a droid park-keeper very pointedly asks you to calm down a bit, so you get off again.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Bouncy castle - 2 - roomex'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, %s starts jumping up and down. After bouncing a few times, the bouncer decides to liven things up by bouncing sideways into the walls, but almost knocks over one of the children, who calls for a droid park-keeper!
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Bouncy castle - 3 - player'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, you start jumping up and down. You bounce once, twice, three times, getting higher each time, until your head is going higher than the top of the castle walls. You get a lovely view over the rest of the park! After a few moments you start to feel quite light-headed from the exertion, so you decide to get off and rest.
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Bouncy castle - 3 - roomex'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, %s starts jumping up and down... bouncing once, twice, three times, getting higher each time, going higher than the top of the castle walls. Must be a lovely view of the park from that high!
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='Bouncy castle - 4 - player'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, you start jumping up and down. You bounce around with wild abandon, not really paying attention to where you are bouncing, just enjoying yourself hugely - until you suddenly stumble and carom off one of the side walls, off the bouncy castle and towards the patch of grass, treading upon which is forbidden.
         </para>

         <para number='8'>
         For a moment, it looks as though you are going to land right in the middle of it, doing who knows what damage to the fragile stems, but a quick-thinking droid park-keeper calculates your trajectory and dives into your path, tackling you to the ground before you can squish any of the stalks. It helps you up and advises you to be more careful in the future.
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='Bouncy castle - 4 - roomex'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, %s starts jumping up and down. Bouncing around with wild abandon, the bouncer is not really paying attention, just enjoying the fun - until suddenly a mis-bounce results in a carom off one of the side walls, off the bouncy castle and towards the patch of grass, treading upon which is forbidden.
         </para>

         <para number='10'>
         For a moment, it looks as though %s is going to land right in the middle of it, doing who knows what damage to the fragile stems, but a quick-thinking droid park-keeper calculates the trajectory and dives into the bouncer's path; performing a heroic tackle, it saves the greenery from being squished.
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='Bouncy castle - 5 - player'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, you start jumping up and down. You bounce up and down several times and feel in complete control, so you decide to try some acrobatics. You scrunch up into a ball and bounce down then up again; stick your limbs out in front of you in a pike; bounce down into a sitting position, then swivel round and bounce facing the other way; and perform a mid-air somersault.
         </para>

         <para number='12'>
         It's all very impressive, and some of the children applaud as you complete the display with a massive bounce off the castle.
         </para>

         <para number='13' comment='Bouncy castle - 5 - roomex'>
         Clambering onto the bouncy castle, %s starts jumping up and down. Bouncing up and down several times, and appearing in complete control, the bouncer decides to try some acrobatics. There's the scrunch into a ball and bouncing down then up again; the sticking the limbs out in front in a pike; bouncing down into a sitting position, then swiveling round to bounce facing the other way; and even a mid-air somersault.
         </para>

         <para number='14'>
         It's all very impressive, and there is a ripple of applause from some of the children as %s completes the display with a massive bounce off the castle.
         </para>

         <para number='15' comment='Get bouncy castle'>
         Don't be silly - it would be far too heavy for you to move, even if it didn't have a crowd of children bouncing on it.
         </para>

         <para number='16' comment='pop/puncture/deflate'>
         What kind of a cruel being would ruin the fun of the little children that way? Well, obviously, you would - but fortunately, you are prevented from destroying the castle by a droid park-keeper, who restrains you until you promise to leave the bouncy castle alone.
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='roomex'>
         If you have ever wondered what kind of a cruel being would try to ruin the fun of little children, then now you know - %s has just tried to destroy the bouncy castle. Fortunately, a droid park-keeper prevented this shocking act of vandalism, and restrained the miscreant, procuring a promise not to do it again.
         </para>

